refentry.refsect1:
&reftitle.description;
callableclass_meth stringclass_name stringmethod_name
class_meth takes a class name and a method name, and returns a callable which will invoke that static method of that class. Like fun, this is in order to aide the type checker in statically analyzing callbacks passed into and out of functions.

  &reftitle.examples;



    Simple class_meth usage


<?hh

class C {
  public static function f(string $s) {}
}

function test(): void {
  // The type checker cannot determine what function $f refers to. It will reject
  // this in strict mode, but in partial mode will admit it, even though it
  // fails at runtime.
  $f = array('C', 'f');
  $f(1);

  // But, with a call to class_meth(), we can know what function $f refers to,
  // and check its arguments statically. This will produce a type error.
  $f = class_meth('C', 'f');
  $f(1);
}







    class_meth is most useful for callbacks


<?hh

function run_callback((function (string): void) $f, string $s) {
  $f($s);
}

function test2(): void {
  // Although this works at runtime, the type checker will reject this, since an
  // array is not a function.
  run_callback(array('C', 'f'), 'test');

  // But this is acceptable:
  run_callback(class_meth('C', 'f'), 'test');
}







    class_meth used as callback for a filter


<?hh

class C {
  public static function isOdd(int $i): bool {
    return $i % 2 == 1;
  }
}

$v = Vector { 1, 2, 3 };
$v->filter(class_meth('C', 'isOdd')); // returns Vector { 1, 3 }
